Possible next step: **Express the function \( f(x) = 2^{2x+2} + 2^{x+2} + 1 \) in terms of \( y = 2^{x} \), transforming it into a quadratic equation in \( y \).**

\[
\begin{align*}
f(x) &= 2^{2x+2} + 2^{x+2} + 1 \\
&= 4 \cdot 2^{2x} + 4 \cdot 2^{x} + 1 \quad \text{(since \( 2^{2x+2} = 4 \cdot 2^{2x} \) and \( 2^{x+2} = 4 \cdot 2^{x} \))} \\
&= 4y^2 + 4y + 1 \quad \text{(where \( y = 2^{x} \))}
\end{align*}
\]

This transformation simplifies the expression, allowing you to set up and solve the inequalities \( 4 < 4y^2 + 4y + 1 < 49 \) to find the corresponding values of \( y \), and subsequently \( x \).

